# Why do fundamental investing?

In university, I believed that investing is a fool's errand. The average money manager loses to the market. So why do anything other than index?

I believe that's true for most people. Nonetheless, someone has to set prices in a market. Not everyone can be passive.

If you decide to pick stocks, why not become a quant? Simply put, I have strong numerical skills, but I don't believe that they are strong enough to go toe-to-toe with with the top 0.001%.

Investing is the ultimate version of what David Epstein in his book Range calls the "Wicked Domain":
-Feedback is delayed, inaccurate, or entirely absent (if you held bonds in 1998, you were right, but had to wait)
-Rules are shifting, incomplete, and non-existent (market leadership and distruption is always evolving)
-Patterns rarely repeat, and can often mislead you

In wicked domains (as opposed to "kind" domains like chess), skill comes not just from how much you know, but also how you think about what you know. Generalists have an edge, as they can integrate knowledge from different fields to make sense of abstract ideas.

I am a dabbler, and enjoy picking up skills from a variety of domains. I have a high tolerance for uncertainty, and believe I am good at thinking through unfamiliar situations. That said, I have the ability to drill deep when I find something of interest.

I enjoy learning about what Charlie Munger refers to as "mental models"—ways of thinking of things from different domains.

As such, I believe my unique individual skills in problem solving, creativity, and imagination make me uniquely suited to fundamental investing. 
